    <!--               SECTION ONE: PROPORTIONAL SEGMENTS                -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDef_11">• Proportional segments have equal ratios.
\n • Ratios show how lengths compare.
\n • Units don\'t affect proportionality.</string>

    <!-- Q: Do units affect whether two segment pairs are proportional? Answer: False -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefQuestion_11">Do the units of measurement affect whether two pairs of segments are proportional?</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerOne_11">True</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerTwo_11">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerThree_11"></string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_11">False</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryProperties_11">• Ratios stay constant when units change.
\n • Parallel lines create proportional segments.
\n • Related segments on both sides are proportional.</string>

    <!-- Q: Do parallel lines cutting two transversals create proportional segments? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsQuestion_11">Do parallel lines cutting two transversals always create proportional segments?</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerOne_11">True</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_11">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerThree_11"></string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_11">True</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExamples_11">• To construct a fourth proportional x given segments a, b, c (so that a:b = c:x): draw a ray from a point, mark off a and c on it, draw another ray and mark off b, connect the endpoints and draw a parallel — the intersection gives x = bc/a.
\n • To divide a segment in ratio 3:5: draw a ray at any angle from one endpoint, mark 8 equal steps, connect the 8th step to the other endpoint, then draw a parallel through the 3rd step — it divides the original segment in ratio 3:5.
\n • These constructions use only a ruler and compass, relying solely on Thales\' theorem for parallel lines and proportionality.</string>

    <!-- Q: To find a fourth proportional to a, b, c where a:b = c:x, what does x equal? Answer: bc/a -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExQuestion_11">To find the fourth proportional x where a:b = c:x, what is x equal to?</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_11">ab/c</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_11">ac/b</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_11">bc/a</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_11">bc/a</string>

