    <!--               SECTION TWO: SIMILAR TRIANGLES                    -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDef_11">• Similar triangles have equal angles and proportional sides.
\n • Their sides share a constant ratio called the ratio of similitude.
\n • Shapes keep the same form but scale differently.</string>

    <!-- Q: Do similar triangles have equal angles? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefQuestion_11">Do similar triangles always have equal corresponding angles?</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefAnswerOne_11">True</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefAnswerTwo_11">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefAnswerThree_11"></string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_11">True</string>

    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryProperties_11">• Similarity is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive.
\n • A line parallel to a triangle side forms a similar triangle.
\n • Triangles are similar by angles, sides, or proportionality tests.</string>

    <!-- Q: Does a line parallel to one side of a triangle always form a similar triangle? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsQuestion_11">Does a line parallel to one side of a triangle and intersecting the other two sides always form a similar triangle?</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsAnswerOne_11">True</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_11">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsAnswerThree_11"></string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_11">True</string>

    <!-- Fixed typo: 11ab → 2ab -->
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExamples_11">• Find segment MN parallel to the two bases of a trapezoid with bases a and b: by similar triangles, |MN| = 2ab/(a+b) — this is the harmonic mean of a and b.
\n • Proof that the centroid divides each median in ratio 2:1: draw two medians intersecting at G; the triangles on either side are similar by AA (parallel midlines), giving the ratio directly.
\n • To prove two triangles similar by the SAS test: show two sides proportional and the included angle equal, then use the definition of similarity to conclude all sides are proportional.</string>

    <!-- Q: Two similar triangles have sides in ratio 3:1. If the smaller has perimeter 12, what is the larger perimeter? Answer: 36 -->
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExQuestion_11">Two similar triangles have ratio of similitude 3:1. If the smaller triangle has perimeter 12, what is the perimeter of the larger triangle?</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_11">15</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_11">24</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_11">36</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_11">36</string>

