    <!--           SECTION FOUR: ANGLE BISECTOR & POWER OF A POINT       -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <!-- Was !!! EMPTY !!! — written from context (angle bisector / power of a point) -->
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDef_11">• Angle Bisector in a Triangle: The bisector of an interior angle divides the opposite side in the ratio of the two adjacent sides.
\n • Power of a Point: For a point P and a circle, the power equals PA × PB for any chord through P; it is constant regardless of which chord is chosen.
\n • Intersecting Chords: Two chords intersecting inside a circle satisfy PA × PB = PC × PD.</string>

    <!-- Q: Does the angle bisector divide the opposite side proportionally to the adjacent sides? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefQuestion_11">Does the angle bisector of a triangle divide the opposite side in the ratio of the two adjacent sides?</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefAnswerOne_11">True</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefAnswerTwo_11">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefAnswerThree_11"></string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_11">True</string>

    <string name="SectionFourTheoryProperties_11">• Angle bisector divides the opposite side proportionally.
\n • Intersecting chords have equal segment products.
\n • Tangent-secant rule: tangent² = external × total secant.</string>

    <!-- Q: Two chords intersect inside a circle with segments 3, 4 and 6, x. What is x? Answer: 2 -->
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsQuestion_11">Two chords intersect inside a circle. One chord has segments of length 3 and 4; the other has one segment of length 6. What is the other segment length?</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsAnswerOne_11">8</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_11">2</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsAnswerThree_11">4</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_11">2</string>

    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExamples_11">• Altitude from the right angle to the hypotenuse divides it into segments p and q. By similarity: leg a² = p×c and leg b² = q×c, where c = p+q is the hypotenuse.
\n • To find the radius R of a circle given a chord of length 2a at distance d from the center: by the intersecting chords theorem applied to the diameter, a² = d×(2R−d), so R = (a²+d²)/(2d) = √(a²+d²)/2... more precisely R = (a²/d + d)/2.
\n • Tangent-secant from external point P: tangent length t, external secant segment e, full secant length s → t² = e×s. Used to find unknown lengths when one value is missing.</string>

    <!-- Q: Two chords intersect: segments 3×4 = 6×x. What is x? Answer: 2 -->
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExQuestion_11">Chords intersect inside a circle with products 3 × 4 = 6 × x. What is x?</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_11">3</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_11">4</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_11">2</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_11">2</string>

