    <!--             SECTION FIVE: SIMILAR POLYGONS & HOMOTHETY          -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryDef_11">• Similar polygons have equal angles and proportional sides.
\n • Homothety scales shapes from a center with ratio k.
\n • Figures remain similar under transformation.</string>

    <!-- Q: Does homothety preserve the shape (angles) of a figure? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryDefQuestion_11">Does a homothety transformation preserve the angles of a figure?</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryDefAnswerOne_11">True</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryDefAnswerTwo_11">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryDefAnswerThree_11"></string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_11">True</string>

    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryProperties_11">• Perimeter ratio equals the ratio of similitude.
\n • Similar polygons decompose into similar triangles.
\n • Corresponding vertices connect identical structures.</string>

    <!-- Q: If two similar polygons have ratio of similitude k=4, what is the ratio of their perimeters? Answer: 4 -->
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryPropsQuestion_11">Two similar polygons have ratio of similitude k = 4. What is the ratio of their perimeters?</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryPropsAnswerOne_11">16</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_11">4</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryPropsAnswerThree_11">2</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_11">4</string>

    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryWorkedExamples_11">• To inscribe a square in a triangle: construct a square on the base of the triangle. Apply a homothety centered at the apex vertex with ratio k chosen so the top side of the square lands on the two non-base sides — the image square is inscribed.
\n • Homothety with center O and ratio k = 2 maps every point P to P\' where OP\' = 2×OP. The image polygon is similar to the original with all sides doubled.
\n • Two similar polygons with ratio k = 3 have perimeters in ratio 3:1; any corresponding diagonal or height also scales by factor 3.</string>

    <!-- Q: Homothety with ratio k=2 doubles all side lengths. What is the ratio of similitude? Answer: 2 -->
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryWorkedExQuestion_11">A homothety with ratio k = 2 is applied to a polygon. What is the ratio of similitude between the image and the original?</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_11">4</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_11">1/2</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_11">2</string>
    <string name="SectionFiveTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_11">2</string>

